Sanity and Next.js together give you content and commerce without the constraints. Here’s how the integration works — and when it’s worth the complexity.

Most e-commerce brands face the same content problem eventually.
They’ve built a Shopify store that handles commerce well. But they want to publish editorial content — brand stories, fragrance guides, lookbooks, collection narratives — that feels native to the store, not bolted onto it. Shopify’s built-in blog is functional but limited. The content and the commerce feel like they belong to different sites.
The solution I reach for in this situation is a headless CMS — specifically Sanity — paired with a Next.js frontend that pulls content from Sanity and product data from Shopify’s Storefront API. The result is a unified storefront where editorial content and commerce live in the same design system, built on the same codebase, and managed from appropriate interfaces.
This isn’t a simple setup. Here’s what it actually involves, where it delivers real value, and how to approach it if you’re building one.

What Sanity Is and Why It Fits This Use Case
Sanity is a headless CMS — a content management system that stores and serves structured content via API, with no assumptions about how that content will be presented. You define the content schema. Your frontend consumes the content through Sanity’s GROQ query language or GraphQL. The presentation is entirely in your control.
For e-commerce, this matters for several reasons:
Content flexibility without constraints. Shopify’s blog gives you a title, body content, an image, and a few metadata fields. Sanity gives you whatever fields you define. A fragrance brand might build a custom schema for fragrance notes, mood descriptors, occasion tags, and pairing suggestions — fields that don’t exist in any off-the-shelf CMS but are exactly what that brand needs for editorial content.
Real-time preview and live editing. Sanity’s Presentation tool allows content editors to see exactly how their content will render on the frontend as they write it — without a deployment cycle. For marketing teams managing time-sensitive content, this matters.
Structured content that works across surfaces. Because content in Sanity is structured rather than stored as raw HTML, the same content object can be rendered differently depending on context — as a full article page, as a card in a collection grid, as a featured story on the homepage. One source of truth, multiple presentations.

The Architecture: How the Pieces Fit Together
A typical Next.js + Sanity + Shopify setup has three distinct systems:
Shopify handles all commerce: product catalogue, inventory, cart, checkout, orders, payments. Accessed via the Shopify Storefront API from the Next.js frontend.
Sanity handles all content: brand stories, editorial articles, lookbooks, collection narratives, team pages, campaign content. Accessed via GROQ queries from the Next.js frontend.
Next.js is the frontend that pulls from both sources and renders a unified storefront. It handles routing, page generation, data fetching, image optimisation, and the user interface.
The key architectural decision is where the boundaries sit between content and commerce. In practice, there are three common configurations:
Separation: Product pages are built entirely from Shopify data. Content pages are built entirely from Sanity data. The two systems never overlap. This is the simplest to build and maintain.
Enrichment: Product pages are built from Shopify data but enriched with editorial content from Sanity — extended descriptions, origin stories, pairing guides, mood copy. A product in Shopify has a reference to a Sanity document that adds the content layer Shopify’s product fields can’t accommodate.
Deep integration: Content and commerce are fully interwoven. A Sanity article about a fragrance family links directly to products. A collection page in Sanity pulls product data from Shopify and editorial copy from Sanity into a single unified page. This is the most powerful configuration and the most complex to build.
For most brands starting with this stack, the enrichment model is the right starting point — it adds meaningful content capability without requiring a full architectural redesign of how products and content relate.

Setting Up the Sanity Studio
The Sanity Studio is the content management interface your editorial team will use. It’s a React application that you configure, customise, and host — either on Sanity’s managed hosting or on your own infrastructure.
Defining your schema:
Everything in Sanity starts with a schema definition. A schema defines the content types (called document types) and the fields each type contains.
A minimal schema for a fragrance brand’s editorial content might include:
// schemas/article.js
export default {
name: 'article',
title: 'Article',
type: 'document',
fields: [
{
name: 'title',
title: 'Title',
type: 'string',
validation: Rule => Rule.required()
},
{
name: 'slug',
title: 'Slug',
type: 'slug',
options: { source: 'title' }
},
{
name: 'publishedAt',
title: 'Published At',
type: 'datetime'
},
{
name: 'coverImage',
title: 'Cover Image',
type: 'image',
options: { hotspot: true }
},
{
name: 'body',
title: 'Body',
type: 'array',
of: [{ type: 'block' }]
},
{
name: 'relatedProducts',
title: 'Related Products',
type: 'array',
of: [{ type: 'string' }],
description: 'Shopify product handles for related products'
}
]
}The relatedProducts field is where the Sanity-Shopify connection lives — storing Shopify product handles (or IDs) as references that the Next.js frontend uses to fetch product data alongside the article content.

Fetching Sanity Content in Next.js
Sanity provides a JavaScript client library (@sanity/client) for querying content from your Next.js application. Queries are written in GROQ — Sanity's graph-relational query language — which is expressive and efficient for fetching exactly the data you need.
Installing the client:
npm install @sanity/client next-sanityConfiguring the client:
// lib/sanity.js
import { createClient } from '@sanity/client'export const client = createClient({
projectId: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SANITY_PROJECT_ID,
dataset: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SANITY_DATASET,
apiVersion: '2024-01-01',
useCdn: true // false for draft content
})Fetching articles:
// A GROQ query to fetch all published articles
const query = `*[_type == "article" && defined(publishedAt)] | order(publishedAt desc) {
_id,
title,
slug,
publishedAt,
coverImage,
"relatedProducts": relatedProducts
}`const articles = await client.fetch(query)Using with Next.js App Router:
In Next.js 14+ with the App Router, data fetching happens in Server Components by default — which is the right place for Sanity queries, since they don’t need to be interactive and benefit from server-side caching.
// app/articles/page.jsx
import { client } from '@/lib/sanity'const query = `*[_type == "article"] | order(publishedAt desc) {
_id,
title,
slug,
publishedAt,
coverImage
}`export default async function ArticlesPage() {
const articles = await client.fetch(query) return (
<div>
{articles.map(article => (
<ArticleCard key={article._id} article={article} />
))}
</div>
)
}
Combining Sanity Content With Shopify Product Data
The real power of this stack is on pages where content and commerce intersect — an article page that displays related products, or a product page that pulls in editorial copy from Sanity.
Here’s how a combined fetch looks for an article page that shows related products:
// app/articles/[slug]/page.jsx
import { client } from '@/lib/sanity'
import { shopifyFetch } from '@/lib/shopify'const articleQuery = `*[_type == "article" && slug.current == $slug][0] {
title,
publishedAt,
coverImage,
body,
relatedProducts
}`const PRODUCTS_BY_HANDLES_QUERY = `
query ProductsByHandles($handles: [String!]!) {
nodes: products(first: 4, query: $handles) {
edges {
node {
id
title
handle
priceRange {
minVariantPrice {
amount
currencyCode
}
}
featuredImage {
url
altText
}
}
}
}
}
`export default async function ArticlePage({ params }) {
// Fetch article from Sanity
const article = await client.fetch(articleQuery, { slug: params.slug }) // Fetch related products from Shopify if they exist
let relatedProducts = []
if (article.relatedProducts?.length > 0) {
const handlesQuery = article.relatedProducts
.map(h => `handle:${h}`)
.join(' OR ')
const { data } = await shopifyFetch({
query: PRODUCTS_BY_HANDLES_QUERY,
variables: { handles: handlesQuery }
})
relatedProducts = data?.nodes?.edges?.map(e => e.node) || []
} return (
<article>
<ArticleContent article={article} />
{relatedProducts.length > 0 && (
<RelatedProducts products={relatedProducts} />
)}
</article>
)
}This pattern — fetch from Sanity, use the result to conditionally fetch from Shopify — is the core of the enrichment model. The article controls which products appear alongside it, without those products needing to exist in Sanity at all.

Handling Images From Both Sources
One practical complexity of this stack is that images come from two different sources: Sanity’s image CDN and Shopify’s image CDN. Both need to be configured in Next.js’s image domain settings.
// next.config.js
module.exports = {
images: {
remotePatterns: [
{
protocol: 'https',
hostname: 'cdn.sanity.io'
},
{
protocol: 'https',
hostname: 'cdn.shopify.com'
}
]
}
}For Sanity images specifically, the @sanity/image-url library generates optimised URLs with transformation parameters — cropping, resizing, format conversion — without requiring separate image processing infrastructure.
import imageUrlBuilder from '@sanity/image-url'
import { client } from '@/lib/sanity'const builder = imageUrlBuilder(client)export function urlFor(source) {
return builder.image(source)
}// Usage
<Image
src={urlFor(article.coverImage).width(1200).height(630).url()}
alt={article.title}
width={1200}
height={630}
/>
When This Stack Is Worth the Complexity
This is not a setup for every e-commerce brand. The complexity is real and the ongoing maintenance requirement is higher than a standard Shopify theme.
It’s worth it when:

• Your brand publishes regular editorial content that needs to feel native to the store, not like a bolted-on blog

• You need content fields that no off-the-shelf CMS provides — custom fragrance notes schemas, mood systems, ingredient databases

• You have a content team that needs a proper editorial interface, not Shopify’s blog editor

• Your storefront needs performance characteristics that server-rendered Next.js provides and hosted platforms don’t

• You have developer resource to build and maintain the integration
It’s not worth it when:

• You’re an early-stage brand still validating product-market fit

• Your content needs are simple enough that Shopify’s native blog handles them

• You don’t have a developer resource for ongoing maintenance

• Your timeline doesn’t accommodate a 6–10 week build
For brands that sit in the middle — wanting better content capability but not ready for a full headless build — a simpler option is Shopify with a Sanity-powered blog section, keeping the store on Shopify’s native platform while using Sanity only for editorial content served through a subdirectory or subdomain.

The Right Mindset for This Stack
Sanity and Next.js together are genuinely powerful. But power without purpose is just complexity.
The brands that get the most from this stack are the ones who know exactly what they need to build before they start building it. They have a content strategy that requires structured editorial content. They have a product catalogue that benefits from editorial enrichment. They have the team to maintain what they build.
If that’s you — this stack is one of the best available for e-commerce brands that take content seriously. If it isn’t yet — build on Shopify, get to revenue, and migrate when the platform is limiting what you can do rather than what yo
